Round 1 
[Patient] What foods should I eat to help manage my heart failure? 
[Educator] Focus on a diet rich in fruits, veggies, whole grains, and lean proteins.

Round 2 
[Patient] Should I avoid salt in my diet? 
[Educator] Yes, too much salt can make your heart failure worse. Try to limit it.

Round 3 
[Patient] Are there any specific fruits I should eat? 
[Educator] Berries, bananas, oranges, and apples are good choices for heart health.

Round 4 
[Patient] Can I still have dairy products? 
[Educator] Choose low-fat or fat-free dairy options to help manage your heart failure.

Round 5 
[Patient] What about meat, can I still have that? 
[Educator] Opt for lean meats like chicken, turkey, and fish instead of fatty meats.

Round 6 
[Patient] Should I avoid caffeine? 
[Educator] Limit your caffeine intake, as it can affect your heart. Try decaf options.

Round 7 
[Patient] What about alcohol, is that okay? 
[Educator] Limit alcohol intake to protect your heart. Moderation is key for heart health.

Round 8 
[Patient] Can I have sweets and desserts? 
[Educator] Enjoy sweets in moderation. Opt for healthier dessert options like fruit or yogurt.

Round 9 
[Patient] Should I be drinking a lot of water? 
[Educator] Stay hydrated with water, but be mindful of your fluid intake if you have heart failure.

Round 10 
[Patient] Are there any foods I should avoid completely? 
[Educator] Avoid processed foods, high-sodium items, and sugary drinks for better heart health.

Round 11 
[Patient] What about fried foods, should I avoid those? 
[Educator] Limit fried foods as they can be high in unhealthy fats. Opt for baked or grilled options.

Round 12 
[Patient] Can I still have my favorite snacks? 
[Educator] Choose heart-healthy snacks like nuts, seeds, or veggies instead of processed snacks.

Round 13 
[Patient] Should I be cooking at home more often? 
[Educator] Cooking at home allows you to control what goes into your meals for better heart health.

Round 14 
[Patient] Can you give me some sample meal ideas for a heart-healthy diet? 
[Educator] Try a grilled chicken salad, vegetable stir-fry, or a quinoa bowl for nutritious meals.

Round 15 
[Patient] Thank you for all the food recommendations, I feel more confident now. 
[Educator] You're welcome! Remember, making small changes to your diet can make a big difference for your heart health.